"title": "7378: high priest, in NT",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7378",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Under the Roman administration the high priest remained the senior Jewish leader, but his power was limited by Roman supervision.</p>\n<h2>High priests of the NT</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:2\">LUK 3:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:2\">ACT 23:2</a> <em>Annas was high priest from A.D. 6 until deposed by the Roman official, Gratus, in A.D. 15. Though replaced by his son Eleazar and, in A.D. 18, by Caiaphas, his son-in-law, Annas retained his authority in Jewish eyes. Strictly, there could only be one high priest at a time. Ananias, the high priest of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:2\">Ac 23:2</a>, was not related to the family of Annas.</em></p>\n<h2>Grandeur of the high priest</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:10\">JHN 18:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:15\">JHN 18:15</a> <em>The courtyard was within a palace</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:12\">ACT 6:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:1\">ACT 7:1</a> <em>The high priest was president of the Sanhedrin.</em></p>\n<h2>The high priest's connections with Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>Prophesying Jesus Christ's death</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John11:49-John11:50\">JHN 11:49–11:50</a></strong> <em>Words spoken by Caiaphas in a political sense were seen to be prophetic, pointing forward to the sacrificing role the high priest would play in the death of Jesus Christ.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John11:51-John11:52\">JHN 11:51–11:52</a></p>\n<h3>Presiding at Jesus Christ's trial</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:19-John18:24\">JHN 18:19–18:24</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:57-Matt26:59\">MAT 26:57–26:59</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:53-Mark14:55\">MRK 14:53–14:55</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:62-Matt26:65\">MAT 26:62–26:65</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:61-Mark14:64\">MRK 14:61–14:64</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke22:54\">LUK 22:54</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:28\">JHN 18:28</a> <em>Caiaphas, the necessary go-between, brought Jesus Christ before Pilate.</em></p>\n<h2>The high priest's encounters with Peter and John</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:7\">ACT 4:7</a></strong> <em>The teaching of Jesus Christ's resurrection was particularly abhorrent to the Sadducees, the priestly party to which Annas and Caiaphas belonged.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:17\">ACT 5:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:21\">ACT 5:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:29\">ACT 5:29</a></p>\n<h2>The high priest's encounter with Stephen</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:1\">ACT 7:1</a></strong> <em>Stephen was thought to have threatened the temple, the focus of high priestly power.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:57-Acts7:59\">ACT 7:57–7:59</a></p>\n<h2>Encounters of the high priests with Paul</h2>\n<h3>Commissioning Paul to persecute Christians</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:1-Acts9:2\">ACT 9:1–9:2</a></strong></p>\n<h3>Ordering that Paul be struck</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:3\">ACT 23:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:21-John18:23\">JHN 18:21–18:23</a></p>\n<h3>Taking charges against Paul to the Roman governor</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts24:1\">ACT 24:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:28\">JHN 18:28</a></p>\n<h2>NT references to OT high priests</h2>\n<h3>Abiathar</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:26\">MRK 2:26</a></strong></p>\n<h3>Melchizedek</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb5:6\">HEB 5:6</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ as high priest</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb4:14-Heb4:16\">HEB 4:14–4:16</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb8:1-Heb8:2\">HEB 8:1–8:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:14\">HEB 9:14</a></p>",
